Q: What did Matthew build at Cisco?
A: At Cisco (Webex Collaboration AI), Matthew built: an MLOps platform for AI/ML model lifecycle management using Airflow and MLflow; a synthetic data pipeline that cut data-creation effort by ~90%; LLM guardrails and safety features (content filtering, prompt injection defense, jailbreak prevention, toxicity detection) protecting millions of Webex users; an automated testing framework for AI agent validation; CI/CD pipelines with Weights & Biases integration for real-time visibility; a business metrics library standardizing collection across 8+ microservices with Grafana dashboards; a multilingual guardrails PoC with linguistics partners; an OCR + parsing pipeline enabling RAG document ingestion; and computer vision pipelines for video enhancements including background blur, virtual backgrounds, and relighting.

Q: What AI safety and security work has Matthew done at Cisco?
A: At Cisco, Matthew designed and shipped LLM guardrails and safety features protecting millions of Webex users — including models for content filtering, prompt injection defense, jailbreak prevention, and toxicity detection. He built autonomous red-teaming agents to test AI systems and identified mis-categorized edge cases in security classifiers to improve model accuracy. He also delivered measurable improvements to security classifiers through synthetic data pipelines enabling continuous fine-tuning.

Q: What MLOps experience does Matthew have?
A: Matthew architected a comprehensive MLOps platform at Cisco using Airflow and MLflow for AI/ML model lifecycle management. He established organizational standards for continuous training, monitoring, and deployment adopted across multiple teams, built CI/CD pipelines pushing metrics to Weights & Biases for real-time visibility, and became the go-to technical authority for MLOps strategy across the organization.

Q: What synthetic data work has Matthew done?
A: Matthew designed and shipped a modular synthetic data pipeline at Cisco that reduced data-creation effort by ~90%. The system supports multilingual expansion and multiple classification domains including toxicity and harm detection. New training sets can be generated in minutes instead of days.

Q: What video or computer vision work has Matthew done?
A: Matthew built computer vision pipelines at Cisco delivering smooth, low-latency video enhancements for millions of Webex users worldwide — including background blur, virtual backgrounds, and relighting, optimized for efficient performance across diverse hardware.

Q: What RAG or document ingestion work has Matthew done?
A: Matthew architected an OCR and document parsing pipeline as a hosted service at Cisco, taking it from proof-of-concept to production. This enables retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) workflows for Webex's AI features.

Q: What did Matthew do at BandLab?
A: At BandLab Technologies (November 2019 – April 2022), Matthew owned audio software features from design to delivery for a global music-creation platform. He built cross-platform applications using C++, the JUCE framework, and audio plugin SDKs (VST/AU), and worked across GUI, DSP, user data persistence, and cloud integration in a distributed team environment.

Q: What consulting work has Matthew done?
A: Matthew runs DayJobDevelopment LLC as a software engineering consultant, focusing on AI/ML audio manipulation, music information retrieval, C++, JUCE, Python, DSP, and web technologies. He has delivered custom software solutions for clients across diverse technical domains.

Q: What programming languages does Matthew know?
A: Matthew's primary programming languages are Python, C++, and Rust. He is most experienced with Python for ML/AI work and C++ for audio software and systems programming. He is also comfortable with JavaScript and web technologies.

Q: What cloud and infrastructure experience does Matthew have?
A: Matthew has hands-on experience with AWS, Azure, Kubernetes, Docker, Pulumi (Infrastructure-as-Code), and GitHub Actions CI/CD pipelines.

Q: What ML frameworks and tools does Matthew use?
A: Matthew works with PyTorch, TensorFlow, scikit-learn, and Hugging Face Transformers. For MLOps he uses Weights & Biases, MLflow, and Airflow. He also has experience with Grafana for dashboards and GitHub Actions for CI/CD.

Q: What AI agent experience does Matthew have?
A: Matthew has built AI agents at Cisco, including autonomous red-teaming agents for testing AI safety systems and an automated testing framework for AI agent validation with objective generation and notification capabilities. He also develops and contributes best practices for AI coding assistants (Claude Code, Codex) to his team's knowledgebase.

Q: Where does Matthew currently work?
A: Matthew currently works at Cisco (Collaboration AI / Webex) as a Senior Software Engineer on the AI Platform team. He joined in June 2022 and is still there.

Q: What companies has Matthew worked for?
A: Matthew has worked at Cisco (Senior Software Engineer - AI Platform, June 2022–present), BandLab Technologies (Software Developer, November 2019–April 2022), and runs DayJobDevelopment LLC as a software consultant. Earlier roles include Ipswich Bay Glass (drafting automation), SARC Inc (design engineering), and Vacuum Technology Inc (solutions engineering).

Q: How many years of experience does Matthew have?
A: Matthew has over 10 years of professional software engineering experience. He started with mechanical engineering software and CAD automation, moved into audio software and DSP, then transitioned into AI/ML engineering where he has been focused since 2022 at Cisco.

Q: What is Matthew's background before AI/ML?
A: Before focusing on AI/ML, Matthew worked in audio software engineering at BandLab Technologies (2019–2022), building cross-platform audio applications and plugins in C++ with JUCE and VST/AU SDKs. He also ran his own consulting practice (DayJobDevelopment LLC) focused on audio, music technology, and AI/ML audio manipulation.

Q: Where did Matthew go to school?
A: Matthew earned a Bachelor of Science in Mechanical Engineering from Worcester Polytechnic Institute (WPI) in 2013. He has since completed several ML and programming certifications through Coursera, Kadenze, and freeCodeCamp.

Q: What certifications does Matthew have?
A: Matthew holds certifications in Supervised Machine Learning: Regression and Classification (Coursera), Advanced Learning Algorithms (Coursera), Advanced Audio Plugin Development (Kadenze), Responsive Web Design & JavaScript Algorithms (freeCodeCamp), and Collaborate Effectively for Professional Success (Coursera).

Q: Has Matthew done any mentorship or leadership work?
A: Yes. Matthew mentors colleagues through formal programs at Cisco — his mentees have advanced to new roles, owned major features end-to-end, and are driving positive change on their teams. He regularly briefs senior leadership, leads knowledge transfer through internal presentations, and partners daily with product, platform, linguistics, and security teams.

Q: What cross-functional experience does Matthew have?
A: Matthew works daily with product, security, linguistics, and platform teams to align technical solutions with business goals. He is the go-to technical authority for MLOps strategy at Cisco and regularly presents technical findings to senior leadership.
